<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><!--Transformation version 1.3--><legislativeDoc xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="http://www.lexisnexis.com/xmlschemas/content/public/legislativedoc/1/" schemaVersion="1.0"><legislativeDocHead><citations><citeForThisResource citeDefinition="#7159#349#000022#     1#          265#">Va. Code Ann. § 22.1-265</citeForThisResource></citations><legislativeBodyInfo><jurisdiction><jurisSystem normalizedLongName="Virginia" normalizedShortName="VA"/></jurisdiction></legislativeBodyInfo></legislativeDocHead><legislativeDocBody><statute><level levelType="section"><anchor id="_22.1-265"/><heading><desig>§ 22.1-265.</desig><title>Inducing children to absent themselves</title></heading><bodyText><p>Any person who induces or attempts to induce any child to be absent unlawfully from school or who knowingly employs or harbors, while school is in session, any child absent unlawfully shall be guilty of a Class 3 misdemeanor and may be subject to the penalties provided by subdivision 5 a of subsection B of <citation type="statute" normalizedCite="VACODE 16.1-278.5"><content><span normalizedCite="Va. Code Ann. § 16.1-278.5">§ 16.1-278.5<locator><locatorKey><keyName name="citeReference"/><keyValue value="#7159#349#000016#     1#        278.5#"/></locatorKey></locator></span></content></citation> or <citation type="statute" normalizedCite="VACODE 18.2-371"><content><span normalizedCite="Va. Code Ann. § 18.2-371">§ 18.2-371<locator><locatorKey><keyName name="citeReference"/><keyValue value="#7159#349#000018#     2#          371#"/></locatorKey></locator></span></content></citation>. Upon a finding that a person knowingly and willfully violated the provisions of this section and that such person has been convicted previously of a violation of this section, such person shall be guilty of a Class 2 misdemeanor.</p></bodyText><history><historyGroup groupType="history-citation"><historyItem><bodyText><p>Code